flowRoot.flowPara: Distributional aspects of remaining years of life

All lifetable summary indices are functions of age, but these are usually only calculated for age zero, or sometimes the age at maturity, retirement or some other particular age. We propose to let lifetable summary measures be calculated at any age. We provide some elementary definitions of functions described and derived from the conditional lifespan distribution, and we apply these to human populations. We suggest a selection of applications for late life decisions, such as the decision to bequest or move into a care residence, based on these distributional measures.

Certain lifecourse decisions are made with a kind of forward-looking anticipation of one's own mortality, especially estate planning and related decisions. Typically, the educated guesser refers to the survival curve or the remaining life expectancy at a particular age (i.e., conditioned on one's acheived survival). This might be an adequate summary of information in most instances, but the data wonks among us ought to account for the full spread of potential outcomes. Why? Because different outcomes may have different costs and payoffs for individuals (and families), and these may not average out as parsimoniously as life expectancy (which is just a mean).
Everything depends on the conditional remaining lifespan distribution. At age 0, this is just the same as the lifetable death distribution, d(a), but it scales as you age
Remaining life expectancy itself is also a function of this conditional distribution
